# Co-Development: Web + React Native

When implementing any new UI feature or screen, **always co-develop across both `apps/web` and `apps/react-native`** to maintain feature parity.

## Workflow

1. Start with the web implementation in `apps/web`
2. Immediately create the equivalent in `apps/react-native`
3. Share the same API hooks (same naming, same data shapes)

## Component Mapping

| Web (shadcn/ui) | React Native (NativeWind) |
|-----------------|--------------------------|
| `<Button>` from shadcn | `<TouchableOpacity className="...">` |
| `<Card>` from shadcn | `<View className="...">` |
| `<Input>` from shadcn | `<TextInput className="...">` |
| `<Dialog>` from shadcn | `<Modal>` from react-native |
| Next.js `<Link>` | Expo Router `<Link>` |

## Structure Parity

- Web pages: `apps/web/src/app/(routes)/feature/page.tsx`
- RN screens: `apps/react-native/app/(tabs)/feature.tsx` or nested routes

## Hook Naming

Use identical hook names in both apps:
- `useGetUsers()` — same name in both `apps/web/src/hooks/` and `apps/react-native/hooks/`
- Same request/response types

## Do NOT

- Implement a feature in web only and "plan to add mobile later"
- Copy-paste web components into React Native (the rendering layer is different)
- Use web-only APIs in shared hook logic (e.g., `window`, `document`)
